# Project VIC Brand and Design System

Project VIC mission tools may use the Project VIC International brand and design system. Visible surfaces should align with that system unless the user explicitly chooses a different brand or agency design system.

## Source of Truth

Use the Project VIC International brand and design system as the default source for:

- Color.
- Typography.
- Spacing.
- Radii.
- Shadows.
- Motion.
- Iconography.
- Components.
- Voice, tone, terminology, and forbidden phrases.

When the public repository is available, prefer a pinned tagged release rather than an unpinned `main` dependency.

## Visible Surfaces

Brand and design guidance applies to:

- Human UI.
- Human-readable API errors and documentation.
- CLI banners, help text, and progress messages.
- Reports, cover sheets, screenshots, diagrams, documentation, and release notes.

Machine-readable CASE/UCO/CAC payloads should stay content-focused and brand-neutral.

## Implementation Rules

- Use semantic tokens rather than hardcoded colors, fonts, spacing, or radii.
- Do not use real or recognizable case content in screenshots, mockups, demos, generated images, or docs.
- Use operator-appropriate language for investigator and examiner workflows.
- Avoid unnecessary ML or engineering jargon in operator-facing copy.
- Use canonical Project VIC naming and terminology.
- Preserve accessibility, including WCAG contrast expectations for UI and reports.

## Speckit Integration

Specs for visible changes should identify:

- Which visible surfaces are affected.
- Which tokens, components, and terminology rules apply.
- How accessibility will be checked.
- What screenshots, docs, reports, or release notes need updates.

## Create a Brand and Design Program for your Organization

- If you are only building one application, you can just create the brand and design system for that app.
- If you intend to create more than one application or use agentic AI tools like Cursor to update and maintain existing applications, it is most helpful to create a new repository and work with the agent to create an organization-wide brand and design system. Reach out to Project VIC International at projectvic.org if you need assistance in doing this. An organizational wide approach is very helpful in maintaining standards.

